### TITLE ###
GuardWithReturnNotLastStmt
### DESCRIPTION ###
Regression: `if err: log(); return` should be detected as
diverging, even though `return` isn't the last statement (it's
second-to-last; the body sees log() as the last statement).
Phase 4e's shallow check missed this; the deep scan catches it.
### INPUT ###
fn f(x: int?):
    if x == null:
        print("missing")
        return
    y = x
### STDOUT ###
# Identifier types
  x @ 2:8 -> int?
  print @ 3:9 -> dynamic
  y @ 5:5 -> <no-type>
  x @ 5:9 -> int

# Symbol types
  f (fn): fn(int?)
  x (param): int?
  y (local): int

# Diagnostics
  (none)
### TITLE ###
NestedIfReturnPropagatesDivergence
### DESCRIPTION ###
A diverging if at any depth in the body makes the body divergent.
After the inner if returns on null, the outer body's fall-through
sees x as int.
### INPUT ###
fn f(x: int?):
    if x == null:
        if true:
            return
        else:
            return
    y = x
### STDOUT ###
# Identifier types
  x @ 2:8 -> int?
  y @ 7:5 -> <no-type>
  x @ 7:9 -> int

# Symbol types
  f (fn): fn(int?)
  x (param): int?
  y (local): int

# Diagnostics
  (none)
### TITLE ###
ExitCallDivergesBranch
### DESCRIPTION ###
`exit()` is a builtin that never returns. A branch ending in
exit() should be treated as divergent, propagating the opposite
refinement to the fall-through.
### INPUT ###
fn f(x: int?):
    if x == null:
        exit(1)
    y = x
### STDOUT ###
# Identifier types
  x @ 2:8 -> int?
  exit @ 3:9 -> dynamic
  y @ 4:5 -> <no-type>
  x @ 4:9 -> int

# Symbol types
  f (fn): fn(int?)
  x (param): int?
  y (local): int

# Diagnostics
  (none)
### TITLE ###
ExhaustiveSwitchAllCasesDivergeNoDefault
### DESCRIPTION ###
A switch over a closed enum that covers every case and where each
case diverges should be treated as a divergent statement - even
without an explicit default arm.
### INPUT ###
fn f(x: ["a", "b"]):
    switch x:
        case "a":
            return
        case "b":
            return
    y = "unreachable"
### STDOUT ###
# Identifier types
  x @ 2:12 -> ["a", "b"]
  y @ 7:5 -> <no-type>

# Symbol types
  f (fn): fn(["a", "b"])
  x (param): ["a", "b"]
  y (local): str

# Diagnostics
  (none)
### TITLE ###
WhileTrueWithBreakDoesNotDiverge
### DESCRIPTION ###
A `while:` with a top-level break inside is NOT divergent - the
break exits the loop and the fall-through runs.
### INPUT ###
fn f():
    while:
        if true:
            break
    y = "ran"
### STDOUT ###
# Identifier types
  y @ 5:5 -> <no-type>

# Symbol types
  f (fn): fn()
  y (local): str

# Diagnostics
  (none)
